
test_ecies: Test ECIES Encrypt and Decrypt modes of operation for
            input data in the container sample

Input required for ECIES operation:
- Plain Data to be encrypted
- Shared info (optional)
- Tag length (can be 0)
- Key

Output:
- Cipher Data
- Tag (if tag length != 0)

To run (load and start) container:
$ mwtest.py -c100 run test_ecies.img

Example for for encrypting some data and then decrypting it:

1) Send open command to open ecies context. The argument is 0 for HC
   and 1 for HC2.

$ cmtest cmd -f100 open 0

2) Send an init command with encrypt op and the recipient's public key.
   The argument 0 after encrypt is the ECIES mode. See list of modes at the
   end of this document. The empty argument at the end is the private key,
   which must be empty ('') for encrypt.

cmtest cmd -f100 init encrypt 0 %d0720dc691aa80096ba32fed1cb97c2b620690d06de0317b8618d5ce65eb728f ''
00000000: f2 01 07 14 80 b9 97 99  70 e4 a9 30 cc c5 30 1a  |........p..0..0.|
00000010: 82 c0 18 b3 94 78 ee 0e  72 a7 6c d3 8c c8 7f 7c  |.....x..r.l....||

The output of the init encrypt command is the message's public key, which need
to be passed to the decrypt command when decrypting.

Note: if you redirect output of cmtest command into a file (or pipe), raw
      bytes are written, instead of the hexdump.

3) Send the data to encrypt with the update command in chunks of length
   multiple of 16 (except last one).

$ cmtest cmd -f100 update %41414141414141414141414141414141
Sending data to CMRT via SIC...
...received 16 bytes OK
00000000: e1 40 66 73 8d fc 6a 88  07 71 25 84 70 89 42 ff  |.@fs..j..q%.p.B.|

...

4) Send the last block of data using the final command. If its length is not
   a multiple of 16, pad it with zeroes. The number in the first argument is
   the tag length. In this case 16, it could be 0. The last argument is the
   shared data, which can be empty ('').

cmtest cmd -f100 final 16 %42424242424242424242424242420000 'shared data'
00000000: 16 4f 86 9d 10 a4 ed 1f  d2 ab 34 d6 7f 36 36 6a  |.O........4..66j|
00000010: a3 d0 15 da 59 ca 49 b7  b3 be 99 5d 92 6c 55 7d  |....Y.I....].lU}|

The first taglen bytes (16 in this case) is the tag. The rest is the output.

5) Now the ECIES context can be closed.

$ cmtest cmd -f100 close

To decrypt, the operation is identical but the init command must be given the
message public key instead of the recipient's public key, followed by the
recipient's private key (which was empty for encrypt).

$ cmtest cmd -f100 open 0
$ cmtest cmd -f100 init decrypt 0 %f201071480b9979970e4a930ccc5301a82c018b39478ee0e72a76cd38cc87f7c %c9806898a0334916c860748880a541f093b579a9b1f32934d86c363c39800357
00000000: d0 72 0d c6 91 aa 80 09  6b a3 2f ed 1c b9 7c 2b  |.r......k./...|+|
00000010: 62 06 90 d0 6d e0 31 7b  86 18 d5 ce 65 eb 72 8f  |b...m.1{....e.r.|

The output must match the recipient's public key.

Now, the sequence of update and last final command can be repeated but the
ciphertext must be provided. The output will be the cleartext.
The tag which is part of the output of the final command must match.
A mismatch means authentication error, for example, different shared info
provided for encrypt and decrypt.

Note: On receiving data from HLOS, ECIES Encrypt and Decrypt modes of
operation are verified.

To unload container:
$ mwtest.py -c100 unload


# Appendix. ECIES modes

'0'
    /** EC: NIST P-256,
       KDF1 HASH: SHA256
       AES-CBC: AES-CBC-128
       HMAC: HMAC-SHA256 */
    CMRT_ECIES_P256_KDF1_SHA256_AES128_HMAC_SHA256,

'1'
    /** EC: NIST P-384
       KDF1 HASH: SHA384
       AES-CBC: AES-CBC-128
       HMAC: HMAC-SHA384 */
    CMRT_ECIES_P384_KDF1_SHA384_AES128_HMAC_SHA384,

'2'
    /** EC: NIST P-521
       KDF1 HASH: SHA512
       AES-CBC: AES-CBC-256
       HMAC: HMAC-SHA512 */
    CMRT_ECIES_P521_KDF1_SHA512_AES256_HMAC_SHA512,

'3'
    /** EC: NIST P-256
       KDF1 HASH: SHA-3-256
       AES-CBC: AES-128
       HMAC: SHA-3-256 */
    CMRT_ECIES_P256_KDF1_SHA3_256_AES128_HMAC_SHA3_256,

'4'
    /** EC: NIST P-384
       KDF1 HASH: SHA-3-384
       AES-CBC: AES-128
       HMAC: SHA-3-384 */
    CMRT_ECIES_P384_KDF1_SHA3_384_AES128_HMAC_SHA3_384,

'5'
    /** EC: NIST P-521
       KDF1 HASH: SHA-3-512
       AES-CBC: AES-128
       HMAC: SHA-3-512 */
    CMRT_ECIES_P521_KDF1_SHA3_512_AES256_HMAC_SHA3_512
